:::summary
Stoicism is one of the most influential and enduring philosophical schools in Western history, founded in Athens around 300 BC by Zeno of Citium and later transformed by Roman thinkers into a practical guide to virtuous living. Stoics held that virtue is the only true good, that reason governs the universe, and that human happiness depends entirely on the quality of one's character and judgments — not on external circumstances. Its insights have shaped Christian ethics, cognitive psychology, and leadership philosophy across two millennia.
:::

